	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>SADC: Progress on tariff liberalisation but less on NTBs</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 December 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The South Africa-based Trade Law Centre (TRALAC) has published a review of SADC’s progress in regional integration. The paper maintains that ‘SADC has made significant progress in liberalising trade’, with most SADC countries having ‘reduced and eliminated tariffs and quotas under the Protocol on Trade since 2000’. However, beyond this ‘shallow integration’, customs coordination and trade facilitation issues need to be addressed, as there has been less progress in these areas. The paper observes that ‘it is not very clear whether all member states remain committed to integration in such behind-the-border issues.’ Equally, progress in regulatory integration ‘appears to be constrained by overlapping membership’ of different regional groupings.</p><p>On tariff liberalisation, the review notes that ‘maximum tariff liberalisation is expected to be achieved in 2012 when the tariff phase-down process for sensitive products would have been completed,’ although Mozambique has until 2015 to ‘complete its tariff phase-down with respect to imports from South Africa’. The paper cites a USAID 2011 audit of the implementation of tariff cuts, which found that:</p>
<ul>

<li>SACU tariff elimination commitments were completed in 2008;</li>

<li>Madagascar, Mauritius, Zambia and Mozambique are on course to complete their tariff phase-down on schedule by the end of 2012;</li>

<li>Tanzania ‘has completed its tariff phase-down, with the exception of sugar’ and some paper products;</li>

<li>Zimbabwe was granted special derogations from its commitments, requiring completion by 2014, although the introduction of some para-tariffs in Zimbabwe is causing concern;</li>

<li>Malawi ‘has been falling behind’, having only implemented around 46% of its commitments, although it expects to have caught up by the end of 2012.</li>

</ul>
<p>However, the use of certain provisions could potentially undermine implementation of the Trade Protocol if used to reverse tariff liberalisation commitments already undertaken. One such provision is Article 3 (1) (c), under which ‘Member States which consider they may be or have been adversely affected by removal of tariffs and non-tariff barriers (NTBs) to trade may…be granted a grace period to afford them additional time for the elimination of tariffs and NTBs.’</p><p>The paper also notes that rules of origin remain problematical, with SADC rules of origin being seen as ‘complex’ and an important factor in the low use of SADC preferential tariff arrangements. The paper records that the rules of origin emerged in ‘a trade-off between substantial tariff liberalisation and restrictive rules of origin’, which saw the establishment of ‘restrictive product specific rules’ linked to regional industrialisation objectives. For example, ‘wheat flour continues to be traded on [a] non-preferential basis… as no rule could be agreed upon’. Rules of origin requirements on processed food products also continue to restrict intra-regional trade development.</p><p>The TRALAC paper observes that a number of other commitments remain largely unfulfilled, including:</p>
<ul>

<li>the adoption and implementation of ‘policies to eliminate existing NTBs’ and refrain from introducing new NTBs; </li>

<li>a prohibition on the application of new quantitative restrictions and phasing out of existing restrictions.</li>

</ul>
<p>These observations are based on ‘complaints reported on the online web-based mechanism’ to monitor NTBs, and the review notes that such provisions ‘continue to be the main impediment to intraregional trade in the COMESA-EAC-SADC region’, with agricultural products being particularly affected, given their perceived links to broader food security and poverty eradication concerns.</p><p>The paper notes finally that the target date for the creation of the SADC Customs Union is ‘unlikely to be realised in the near future’. Most members continue to pursue customs union ambitions in other frameworks (e.g. COMESA and the EAC).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>TRALAC, ‘Regional integration in SADC: Retreating or forging ahead’, by P. Kalenga, <i>Working Paper </i>no. S12WP08/12<i>, </i>September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/files/2012/09/S12WP082012-Kalenga-Regional-integration-in-SADC-retreating-or-forging-ahead1.pdf" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/files/2012/09/S12WP082012-Kalenga-Regional-integra...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Non-tariff trade policy measures continue to be used extensively in the SADC region. Import and export quotas are extensively used for wheat and wheat flour, maize and maize meal, poultry, tobacco, sugar, salt, eggs, and fruit and vegetables, while import levies, import permits and licensing are used to regulate the trade in milk (sterilised and UHT milk), pasta, sorghum, eggs, sugar, dairy, livestock, pork, poultry, liquor/beer, and wheat. Export taxes are used for dried beans, live animals, hides and skins, sugar, tobacco, maize, meat, wood, and coffee, while export bans have been implemented by SADC governments on wheat and wheat flour, maize, beer, poultry, meat products and milk (sterilised and UHT).</p><p>The use of these agricultural trade policy tools by various SADC member states stems from the application of Articles 9 and 10 of the SADC Trade Protocol, which allows for exceptions where the applicant cites legitimate public policy objectives. The most frequently cited public policy objective is national food security.</p><p>While this can be seen as legitimate, given the huge disparities in size and levels of economic development among SADC members states (most notably in respect of South Africa) and the agreed basis for these exceptions under the SADC Trade Protocol, an important lesson from the experience in the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) is that the application of these permitted trade policy tools should be transparent and accountable to regional bodies. This is essential if the use of agreed trade policy measures is not simply to degenerate into open-ended protectionism, supporting inefficient practices.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
